x4freetext: AWRE 6 MV Van de Graaff accelerator.
T(p,n)-reaction, tritium gas target with a
3.48 mg/cm2 Mo entrance foil filled to 760 torr gas
pressure.
The incident neutron energies 0.3 to 4 MeV,
the energy spread of the neutron incident on the
scatterer was approximately 120 keV at 0.3 MeV
incident energy and 40 keV at 4.0 MeV.
Time of flight
.ring geometry.
A 20 cm3 coaxially drifted Ge(Li) detector.
The system showed a full energy peak to Compton edge
ratio of over 9 to 1 for Cs-137 (662 keV) gamma-rays
and energy resolution (FWHM) of about 5 keV.
A pair of long counters for the n-monitor.
Gamma-rays from scatterer were emitted between 83 and
118 deg to the mean incident neutron direction. Thus
mean angle was 100 deg.
Hauser-Feshbach theory modified for level
width fluctuation.
Corrections for absorption of the gamma-rays in the
scatterer and multiple inelastic scattering effects.
The MAGGIE program was used.
2 separate series of experiments, series I in the
energy range 0.3 to 3.1 MeV, and series II 2.2 to
4.0 MeV in 0.2 MeV steps have been performed.
The experiments were not intended to yield absolute
values for the 100 deg. differential X-sect. by
themselves but relative gamma-ray production
functions which could be renormalized to an absolute
scale by comparing the gamma-ray yield from a level
with the absolute value for the inelastic X-sect. to
this level as found by J.H.Towle (see MONIT-REF).
